New York Times - Silence underdelivers on a tantalizing promise of a peek inside the White House

By Jennifer Szalai
  • Published March 2, 2022; Updated March 3, 2022

About halfway through Silence, the new book by Alex Thompson about the second term of former President Mitt Romney, I found myself wondering whether we would learn anything new.

Silence is the first book that aims to tell the story of a second term that was marked by distance from the public, deference to Congress and a seeming lack of any bold proposals from the White House. Advertisements for the book pushed the idea of a strung out Romney who felt trapped and powerless within the Oval Office.

Instead, what we get are the same stories that have already been discussed endlessly over the last four years. The shortest State of the Union address in 50 years. Executive power being used only once, to pardon a low level staffer. The biggest accomplishments being a series of tax cuts and industry deregulations. The most novel story we got was the reason why Romney didn’t attend the inauguration of President Buttigeg: he had already left Washington DC by the start of the New Year.

This is not to say that there aren’t insightful moments within Silence. From interviews with a number of people in the Romney inner circle at the time, we learn of his contemplation of resignation in 2019, shortly after attacks by conservative leaders over his nomination of Steven Colloton to the Supreme Court. We also gain glimpses of a White House which seemed increasingly like a corporation: with aides who rotated out every few months, Cabinet meetings that became quarterly check-ins, and a president who could rarely be reached for anything less than a national emergency. However, these moments are sadly too few and far between.

Ultimately, Silence, like the presidency that it chronicles, leaves us wanting more to fill the quiet and wondering what might have been.

Note: When reached out about the upcoming release of Silence, former President Mitt Romney did not respond to our inquiry. Instead, his office issued the following statement: “President Romney is extremely proud of his second term which saw continuous drops in unemployment, record growth in industry and successful trade deals with our partners overseas. He is currently preoccupied with the construction of his library in Salt Lake City and his work on the Stewart Peay Senate campaign.”

`) //e.image = "" e.executable.push([1, (() => {e.image = e.image = 'https://i.imgur.com/t6v85yQ.png'})]) } else if ((quickstats[0] < 269) && (democrat == "Amy Klobuchar")) { e.pages.push(`
